1 Intro

Through this tutorial you should get familiar with the structure of the SingleCellExperiment object, and basic functions for manipulation, and quality control of the single cell expression data.

1.1 Single Cell Experiment Object

SingleCellExperiment object is a container for single cell data. It is build upon the SummarizedExperiment object, with the following structure

SingleCellExperiment

1.2 The Data

For this workshop we will use the publicly available data set, provided by 10x genomics. The count matrix can be found on the following link: link.

We have pre-processed the data into a hdf5 file. hdf5 file format is constructed for fast manipulation with array based data types (i.e. matrices). It stores indexed location for fast random access. You can consider the hdf5 file like a 2d bam file.

2 Exercises

2.0.1 Constructing SingleCellExperiment Objects

From the files in the data folder construct the SingleCellExperiment object. Hint: h5ls, HDF5Array, SingleCellExperiment

First you will need to connect to the hdf5 object. Then you will pass the object to the SingleCellExperiment constructor.

To connect to the hdf5 file, you will need the name of the saved matrix. This information can be obtained using the h5ls function

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(HDF5Array))
input_hdf5 = 's10x_3cells.hdf5'
name = h5ls(input_hdf5)$name

mat = HDF5Array(file=input_hdf5, name=name)

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(SingleCellExperiment))
sce = SingleCellExperiment(
     assays  = list(counts=mat))

2.0.2 What is the size of the constructed single cell experient?

print(object.size(sce),units='Mb')
## 0.1 Mb

2.0.4 Add the gene names, and biotypes to the SingleCellExperiment object

The table genes.tsv contains ENSEMBL gene ids for the corresponding rows of the expression matrix. Load the table into R.

Using the biomaRt package, download the gene names and gene biotypes for the genes in the SingleCellExperiment object, and update the gene annotations. Hint: useMart, getBM, rowData

gene_names = read.table('genes.tsv')

library(biomaRt)
mart = useMart(biomart = "ensembl", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")
bm   = getBM(mart       = mart,
             attributes = c('ensembl_gene_id','hgnc_symbol','gene_biotype'),
             filters    = 'ensembl_gene_id',
             values     = gene_names$V1)

bm = bm[match(gene_names$V1, bm$ensembl_gene_id),]

rowData(sce) = DataFrame(bm)

3.0.2 Remove all genes which have less than 100 reads in all cells

Hint: DelayedMatrixStats package

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(DelayedMatrixStats))
rs = DelayedMatrixStats::rowSums2(assays(sce)$counts)
sce = sce[rs > 100,]

3.0.3 What is the number of expressed genes per cell?

First count the number of 0 values, per cell. Hint: DelayedMatrixStats::colCounts

zero = DelayedMatrixStats::colCounts(assays(sce)$counts, value=0)

dropout = round(zero/nrow(sce),2)

Add the dropout rate to the column descriptors of the SingleCellExperiment object.

colData(sce)$dropout = dropout

3.0.4 Plot the dropout rate Vs average expression

Now plot the dropout rate Vs the average expression of expressed genes, per cell.

csum   = DelayedMatrixStats::colSums2(assays(sce)$counts)
ngenes = nrow(sce) - zero
colData(sce)$total_counts = csum
colData(sce)$mean_expr    = round(csum/ngenes, 2)
as.data.frame(colData(sce)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=mean_expr, y=dropout)) +
    geom_point()

3.1 Scale the data

Create a function which will scale the normalized expression values. Scaling is defined as subtracting the mean, and dividing by the standard deviation. This operation is useful for making relative comparisons between genes, and visualizing differences between gene expression.

scaleDM = function(dm) {
  #subtract column means from corresponding columns 
  cdm = t(dm - DelayedMatrixStats::rowMeans2(dm)) #centred delayed matrix
  #scale
  scdm = t(cdm / DelayedMatrixStats::rowSds(cdm)) #scaled centered delayed matrix
  return(scdm)
}

assays(sce)$scale = scaleDM(assays(sce)$logcounts)

3.2 Find the cell cycle markers

First read in the cell cycle genes from the human_cycle_markers.rds, which is provided with the scater package. Hint: system.file

cc.pairs = readRDS(system.file("exdata", paste0("human_cycle_markers.rds"), package="scran"))

Using the cyclone function calculate the cell cycle phase for each gene. Add the results to the colData of the SingleCellExperiment object. Cells that did not end with an assigned cell cycle phase mark as unknown.

assigned = scran::cyclone(x = sce, 
                          gene.names = rowData(sce)$ensembl_gene_id, 
                          assay.type = 'logcounts', 
                          pairs      = cc.pairs)

phases = assigned$phases
phases[is.na(phases)] = 'unknown'
colData(sce) = cbind(colData(sce), DataFrame("CellCyclePhase" = phases))

4 Dimensinallity Reduction

In this section you will learn how to use the dimensionallity reduction methods on the SingleCell experiment objects.

4.1 PCA

Using the runPCA function from the scater package, calculate the first 5 principle components for the data.

Where does the function store the principle components? How can you access them?

sce = scater::runPCA(object         = sce, 
                     ncomponents    = 5, 
                     pca_data_input = 'logcounts')

Using the plotPCA function, overlay the cell cycle phase on the scatterplot of PC1 Vs PC2.

scater::plotPCA(object         = sce, 
                colour_by      = 'CellCyclePhase',
                pca_data_input = 'logcounts')

Now plot the first principal component Vs 2nd to 5th principal component, and color the plots by the dropout rate

dat = as.data.frame(colData(sce)) %>%
    cbind(as.data.frame(reducedDims(sce)$PCA)) 
gl = lapply(2:5, function(x){
    dat %>%
    ggplot(aes_string('PC1',paste0('PC',x), color='dropout')) +
        geom_point() +
        scale_color_gradient2(midpoint=0.7)
})

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(cowplot))
plot_grid(plotlist = gl, nrow=1)

Repeat the same figure, but with the cell cycle phase.

dat = as.data.frame(colData(sce)) %>%
    cbind(as.data.frame(reducedDims(sce)$PCA)) 
gl = lapply(2:5, function(x){

5 Gene Exploration

5.0.1 Finding highly variable genes

In this section you will use variance decomposition methods to extract genes whoose biological variance is higher than the technical variance - i.e. to extract differentially expressed genes.

Append the resulting table to the rowData object.

Hint: normalize, trendVar, decomposeVar

sce    = normalize(sce)
fit    = scran::trendVar(x = sce, assay.type = 'logcounts', use.spikes = FALSE)
decomp = scran::decomposeVar(x = sce, fit = fit, assay.type = 'logcounts')
rowData(sce) = cbind(rowData(sce), 
                      DataFrame(decomp))

5.0.2 Plot the mean - variance plot

Using the previously computed decomposed variance object, plot the average logCPM Vs total variance scatter plot. Label the top 10 genes. Fit a line which corresponds to the estimated technical variance.

Mark the top 10 genes with the lowest p value, and plot their gene names.

data = as.data.frame(rowData(sce))
top_genes = data  %>%
    dplyr::arrange(FDR) %>%
    head(20)

data %>%
    ggplot(aes(mean, total)) +
    geom_point(size=.5) +
    geom_line(data = data, aes(mean, tech), color='red', size=2) +
    xlab('Mean log-expression') +
    ylab('Variance') +
    geom_point(data = top_genes, aes(mean, total), color='red') +
    geom_text(data = top_genes, aes(label = hgnc_symbol))

5.0.3 Gene expression heatmap

Plot top 50 genes that contribute to principle component 1. For this you will need the contribution of each gene to each principle component (gene loadings).

First, run the prcomp function to extract, and extract the gene loadings.

results = stats::prcomp(x = assays(sce)$scale, 
                       center = FALSE, 
                       scale. = FALSE, 
                       rank   = 2)

rowData(sce) = cbind(rowData(sce), DataFrame(results$x))

Now select the top 50 genes with the highest gene loadings to PC1, and plot a heatmap of their scaled expression values. (if you don’t have scaled expression values, go to Scale the data)

Hint: ComplexHeatmap::Heatmap

top_genes = as.data.frame(rowData(sce)) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(-PC1) %>%
    head(50)

sce_sub = sce[rowData(sce)$ensembl_gene_id %in% top_genes$ensembl_gene_id,]

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ComplexHeatmap))
dat = data.frame(as.matrix(assays(sce_sub)$scale))
rownames(dat) = rowData(sce)$hgnc_name
Heatmap(dat, show_row_names = FALSE, show_column_names = FALSE)

5.1 Gene expression on tSNE

Find the top 4 genes with highest biological variance, and overlay their expression on the tSNE. Arrange the plots in a rectangle. Hint: cowplot::plot_grid

dat = as.data.frame(colData(sce)) %>%
    cbind(as.data.frame(reducedDims(sce)$TSNE)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE1 = V1) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE2 = V2)

genes = as.data.frame(rowData(sce)) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(-bio)

gl = lapply(1:4, function(i){
    ind = rowData(sce)$ensembl_gene_id == genes$ensembl_gene_id[i]
    dat %>%
        dplyr::mutate(expr = assays(sce)$scale[ind,]) %>%
        ggplot(aes(tSNE1, tSNE2, color=expr)) +
        geom_point() +
        scale_color_gradient2(midpoint=2.5) +
        ggtitle(genes$hgnc_symbol[i])
})
library(cowplot)
plot_grid(plotlist=gl)

6 Clustering

scran package contains two functions for clustering of the single cell data. Explore the quickCluster function. What types of cluterings does it provide?

Execute the provided clustering altgorithms, and overlay the results on the tSNE.

colData(sce)$cluster = scran::quickCluster(sce, 
                     min.size   = 1,
                     method     = 'igraph',
                     assay.type = 'logcounts',
                     pc.approx  = TRUE,
                     d          = 150, 
                     rand.seed  = 1)
colData(sce)$cluster_hier = scran::quickCluster(sce, 
                     min.size   = 10,
                     method     = 'hclust',
                     assay.type = 'logcounts')
g1 = as.data.frame(colData(sce)) %>%
    cbind(as.data.frame(reducedDims(sce)$TSNE)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE1 = V1) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE2 = V2) %>%
    ggplot(aes(tSNE1, tSNE2, color=cluster)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_color_brewer(palette='Set1')


g2 = as.data.frame(colData(sce)) %>%
    cbind(as.data.frame(reducedDims(sce)$TSNE)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE1 = V1) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE2 = V2) %>%
    ggplot(aes(tSNE1, tSNE2, color=cluster_hier)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_color_brewer(palette='Set1')

plot_grid(g1, g2)

6.0.1 Consensus based clustering

Bioconductor provides many additional clustering methods which can be used for the analysis of single cell data: ClusterExperiment, SC3 …

If you lasted until here, install the SC3 package from Bioconductor, and try the clustering algorithm on the dataset. Overlay the results on the tSNE.

This is still in development, so try to overcome the errors.

library(SC3)
rowData(sce)$feature_symbol = rowData(sce)$hgnc_symbol
sce_mat = sce
assays(sce_mat) = lapply(assays(sce_mat), as.matrix)
sc = sc3(sce_mat, ks = 6, biology=FALSE, rand_seed=1)
as.data.frame(colData(sc)) %>%
    cbind(as.data.frame(reducedDims(sc)$TSNE)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE1 = V1) %>%
    dplyr::rename(tSNE2 = V2) %>%
    ggplot(aes(tSNE1, tSNE2, color = sc3_5_clusters)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_color_brewer(palette='Set1')

8.0.3 Dimensionallity reduction using Zinbwave

Zinbwave is a new method for modeling single cell data. Zinbwave can be used for dimensionality reduction, dropout modelling, and differential expression.

For example:

This will take a while

library(zinbwave)
zinb = zinbFit(sce_mat, K=2, epsilon=1000)

W = getW(zinb)
colnames(W) = paste0("W", 1:2)

data.frame(W, bio=colData(sce_mat)$cluster,
           dropout=colData(sce_mat)$dropout) %>%
    ggplot(aes(W1, W2, colour=bio)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    scale_color_brewer(type = "qual", palette = "Set1") + 
    theme_classic()
